As I see it, there are different levels of "on topic" discussions for 
Extropians:

Primary Extropian topics:  those that directly involve the Extropian 
Principles and of interest to Transhumanists more than most humans.  
This would include self-modification, future technology, space 
exploration, etc.

Secondary Extropian topics:  those that don't directly involve the 
Extropian Principles and are of no interest to transhumanists except 
that we need to address them to prevent them from interfering with our 
movement.  This would include Luddites, religion, legal restrictions, 
public opinion, etc.  We probably don't care about these issue except 
that they won't go away and probably need to be monitored.

Tertiary Extropian topics:  those that don't directly involve the 
Extropian Principles and are of interest to all humans equally whether 
they are transhumanists or not.  This would include guns, politics, 
self-defense, computer security, personal finance, etc.  Extropians may 
want to excel in these areas as a support function to the primary 
extropian ideals, but they are of no more importance to transhumanists 
than to any other humans.

Un-extropian topics:  those that don't have anything to do with the 
Extropian Principles and not of any special interest to transhumanists 
or other humans, but we want to discuss anyway.  Jokes, the latest 
movies, updates about how hellish our boss is, meetings for beer, etc.  
Not even related to extropian topics, but communications that humans 
have with their friends anyway.

Anti-extropian topics:  those that run counter to the Extropian 
Principles and are directly avoided by most transhumanists.  (There will 
always be exceptions.)  These topics would probably be off-limits in any 
case, and would include those beliefs that are contradictory to 
transhumanism.  Anti-freedom, anti-science, and other negentropy forces 
would be examples in this category.


While the Primary Extropian topics are definitely desired, it is the 
Secondary and Tertiary topics which create most of the volume.  These 
topics are related to our interests, and are vital in many ways, but are 
also seen as off-topic by many members.  I think these cause the most 
frustration because they are of no interest to large segments of the 
group.


Perhaps we can split these off into other lists somehow.  Comments?


