recently taken to "combat potential terrorism" have led to a slippery slope 
of sorts...one which can only heighten the aforementioned sense of 
xenophobia among the average person.

What does surprise me is the boldness of Le Pen's stance on a number of 
issues, particularly those of immigration and citizenship (going so far as 
talking about revoking citizenships for non-pureblood French stock).  While 
the French are generally identified by their boldness or "snootiness" as it 
may be, Le Pen's stance strikes me as a slap in the face to the makers of 
foreign policy in the other G8 countries, and I sincerely hope that it 
provides a bit of a wake up call to the millions of people worldwide who 
have fallen prey to the cultural xenophobia we are currently 
experiencing.  Sadly, I'm quite concerned that the opposite may be true.

While it may seem that I am overstating the significance of a minority 
leader's political platform, I can honestly foresee that similar views 
could spring up in other economically stable nations in the near 
future.  Woe to us all if they ever become a majority.


